Oh yeah that's a big factor. You know, you should look into testing for genes that contribute to ovarian cancer. That would give you a really good idea of the sort of monitoring and potential future preventative treatment you might need.

But just for ovarian cysts, doctors used to remove the ovary if a woman had a really large cyst. They don't do that anymore unless there's another problem like torsion that can cut off blood supply to the ovary and damage it or kill it. Back when I started having problems there were some old-school doctors who still would remove woman's ovaries and it made me very reticent to seek treatment.

Oophorectomy (ovary removal) is not a treatment for PCOS and actually makes it worse because estrogen plays a role in regulating glucose.

From 16 to 19 I had cysts every month with pain. Then I got on supplemental progesterone, 100mg ovulation to menstruation every month. Now I don't have cysts, or at least they don't grow and cause symptoms.

Other things that help are low carb, high fat and protein diets and metformin.
